Task 1: The DAG

- Come up with an incredibly interesting and scientifically important made-up example for a phenomenon to investigate. Decide on two variables (an outcome and a predictor) that you would like to investigate the relation between. If in doubt, you can be inspired by Peter’s amazing example on the next page.

In our example, we wish to investigate the effect of the predictor corona fear (CF) on the outcome variable Infected (a binary variable taking either the value 0 or 1)

Since Denmark reported it’s first case of COVID-19 contraction on the 27th February 2020 (STPS, 2020), COVID-19 and its development has been subject to extensive coverage in Danish media. News media has a critical role in times of epidemic crises since exposure to as well as consumption of information in times of pandemics may alter people’s perception and provoke behavioural changes that might ultimately impact the evolution and further spread of the virus (Gozzi et al., 2020).

We therefore expect that corona fear is a sensible predictor of whether one gets infected or not, assuming that the degree to which one fears COVID determines the precautions and actions one take to avoid getting infected.

Predictor: corona fear (continuous variable) Outcome variable: infection (0/1) Sanitizing: continuous variable FM variable: do you wear face mask according to the national guidelines? (for the sake of simplicity, we assume that this is a binary variable taking either the value 0 or 1, meaning that you either always where a face mark when the guidelines advises you to do that (1) and never wear it in situations were the national guidelines advises it. We do acknowledge that is a false dichotomy) Germ level: the level of vira germs in your body. We have no biological evidence for a variable of this type, but for the sake of simplicity we assumes that the level of germs present in your body can be describes as a normally distributed continuous variable OCD variable: A categorical variable that takes a value between 1 and 5, which reflects the severity of the OCD condition (Obsessive Compulsive Disorder). 1 being no OCD symptoms at all and 5 being very severe OCD

- Make a DAG for the phenomenon. Make it medium complicated: that means, make sure there are some different kinds of relations (see next step). Change it if you don’t get anything interesting for the next steps.
Draw it somehow (on paper, in R, laser engraved in diamond).
Code it in dagitty (this is a nice tool: http://dagitty.net/dags.html )

- Find elemental forms of variable relations in the DAG (i.e., forks, pipes, colliders, and their descendants).

Pipe

(FM -> GERM LEVEL -> INFECTED)

(Cf –> FM –> GERM)

(CF -> S -> GERM)

(S –> GERM –> INFECTED)

(OCD –> CF –> FM) X

(OCD –> S –> GERM LEVEL)

Fork

(S <- CF -> FM)

(CF <- OCD -> S)

Collider

(S -> GERM LEVEL <- FM)

(CF-> S <- OCD)

Descendant

(OCD –> CF –> FM, CF –> S )

We expect OCD to affect your corona fear in such way that a higher level of OCD increase the level of corona fear.

A typical symptom of OCD is an abnormal fear of germs, which results in highly frequent use of sanitizer. Thus, we assume that the amount of sanitizing will increase with the level of OCD (OBS)

We expect the variable FM to depend on your corona fear, as we assume that a person who is really scared of COVID would be much more likely to strictly follow the national guidelines, whereas a person who didn’t fear corona at all would reversely be much less likely to wear a face mask although the national guidelines advises one to do it

The same goes for the relation between corona fear and sanitising. We expect a person with a high corona fear to have a much higher daily frequency of sanitising than a person with no corona fear at all.

We would expect germ level to depend on whether you wear face mask when advised to or not, as the face mask (at least partly) prevents germs from entering your mouth and nose.

The same goes for the relation between germ level and sanitising, as sanitising works by killing most germs, preventing them from entering your body

Lastly, we expect the level of germs to determine whether you are infected or not. With a low level of germs, one would expect your immune system would be strong enough to fight the few germs that have entered your body. However, if the level of germs in your body is extremely high, it might exceed the capacity of your immune system to fight back, resulting in you getting infected.

*OBS: OCD as a backdoor

Chris: our input is CF (predictor, our intervention), our outcome is (infected). We don’t have any backdoor paths, all paths are causal. If FM was a collider, it would be a common cause/confound that we would have to account for (hold constant) to close the backdown. We could aadd something that affects both FM and Germ_lvl. To have the total causal effect, we only need CF and Inf in out model (if we include FM and S, the coefficient for CF would just return the prior. Tge estimate for htis coefficient would be its own prior).

You can ask your computer to reproduce this analysis, to analyze the graph and find the necessary variables to control for in order to block the backdoor. The dagitty R package provides adjustmentSets for this purpose

In order to shut the backdoor. Here’s the recipe: (1) List all of the paths connecting X (the potential cause of interest) and Y (the out- come). (2) Classify each path by whether it is open or closed. A path is open unless it contains a collider. (3) Classify each path by whether it is a backdoor path. A backdoor path has an arrow entering X. (4) If there are any backdoor paths that are also open, decide which variable(s) to con- dition on to close it. Let’s consider some examples.

Task 3: Statistics

- Run multiple linear regressions to test the conditional independencies implied by your DAG. Make sure to avoid backdoor paths. See that the linear model shows the conditional independencies implied by your DAG, implying that the data and the DAG are compatible (if the linear model doesn’t show the conditional independencies implied by the DAG, the data and the DAG doesn’t fit).

Testing the conditional independencies

Model 1: crn_ || grm_ | fc_m, sntz. Testing whether the causal coefficient germ_level is insignificant when stratifying by face_mask and sanitizing.

m1<- quap(
    alist(
        corona_fear_std ~ dnorm( mu , sigma ) ,
        mu <- a  + bGermLevel*germ_std + bFaceMask*face_mask_std + bSanitizing*sanitizing_std,
        a ~ dnorm( 0 , 0.2 ) ,
        bGermLevel~ dnorm( 0 , 1 ),
        bFaceMask~ dnorm( 0 , 1 ) ,
        bSanitizing ~ dnorm( 0 , 1 ),
        sigma ~ dexp( 1 )
    ) , data = df )

plot(coeftab(m1),by.model=TRUE )

As seen in the above plot, corona fear and germ level becomes independent (i.e., the model with almost no uncertainty estimates the coefficient bGermLevel to be very close to zero ) when stratifying by face_mask and sanitizing.

Model 2: crn_ || infc | grm_ Testing whether the causal coefficient infc (being infected or not) is insignificant when stratifying by germ_level.


m2<- quap(
    alist(
        corona_fear_std ~ dnorm( mu , sigma ) ,
        mu <- a + bInfected*infected_std  + bGermLevel*germ_std,
        a ~ dnorm( 0 , 0.2 ) ,
        bInfected ~ dnorm( 0 , 1 ) ,
        bGermLevel~ dnorm( 0 , 1 ),
        sigma ~ dexp( 1 )
    ) , data = df )

plot(coeftab(m2), par=c("bInfected", "bGermLevel" ))

As seen in the above plot, corona fear and infected becomes independent (i.e., the model confidently estimates the coefficient bInfected to be very close to zero) when stratifying by germ_level.

Model 3: crn_ || infc_ | fc_m, sntz Testing whether the causal coefficient bInfected is insignificant when stratifying by face_mask and sanitizing.

Task 4: Messing it up

- Try and deliberately have an open back door path and see if you can get wrong inference.

Comparing the two models We get wrong inference if we dont include OCD in our model Not including OCD in the model results in a different estimate of the level of corona fear’s influence on the chance of whether you get infected or not, that is zero influence of corona fear on influence. Contrarily, including OCD in the model and thus closing the backdoor, results in an estimate of a negative relationship between level of corona fear and the chance of getting infected.

OBS comment

# Corona fear (assuming that it is normally distributed)
corona_fear_w <-rnorm(N, mean=50, sd=10)

# Face mask (depending on germ level)
face_mask_w <- rbinom(N, size =1, prob= inv_logit(scale(germ_level)))

# Sanitizing (depending on germ_level)
sanitizing_w <- rnorm(N, mean= germ_level-20, sd=2)

# Germ level (depending on corona fear and face mask)
germ_level_w <-  rnorm(N, mean= 5000 - ((corona_fear*10)*(1+face_mask)), sd=100)

# Infected (not depending on any of the variables)
infected_w <-  rbinom(N, size= 1, prob=0.2)


# OCD level
OCD_w <- sample(1:5, size=N, replace=TRUE, prob=c(.8, .10, .05, .03, .02)) # 80% of not having OCD, apx. 2% chance for severe OCD
